<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16093</anchor> <rss>jms-00CQ.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00CQ</addr>  <route>jms-00CQ.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">an algebra</link> for an endofunctor <tex>{ \mathcal{C} } \xrightarrow{{ F }} { \mathcal{C} }</tex>, and let <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ x }} { X }</tex> be an endomorphism in <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>. We define the <em>restriction</em> of <tex>X</tex> by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ x }} { X }</tex> to be the <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">algebra</link> <tex>x \cdot   X</tex> whose carrier is <tex>X</tex> with <tex>{ F X } \xrightarrow{{ \alpha _{ x \cdot X } }} { X }</tex> defined to be the following composite:</p><center><img src="resources/c2d224104b36f5afebbe1b13e5162288-web.svg"/></center></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16094</anchor> <rss>jms-00CJ.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00CJ</addr>  <route>jms-00CJ.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebras for endofunctors and monads</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>16095</anchor> <rss>jms-00C6.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C6</addr>  <route>jms-00C6.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebra for an endofunctor</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>F</tex> be an endofunctor on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>; an <em>algebra</em> for <tex>F</tex> is defined to be an object <tex>X \in \mathcal{C}</tex> equipped with a mapping <tex>{ F X } \xrightarrow{{ \alpha _{ X } }} { X }</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>16096</anchor> <rss>jms-00C7.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C7</addr>  <route>jms-00C7.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Homomorphism of algebras</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>F</tex> be an endofunctor on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> and let <tex>X , Y</tex> be a pair of <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">algebras for <tex>F</tex></link>; a <em>homomorphism</em> of algebras from <tex>X</tex> to <tex>Y</tex> is given by a morphism <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ h }} { Y }</tex> in <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> that preserves the algebra structure in the following sense:</p><center><img src="resources/27974f5a2f310c1a541fc2c0089b509a-web.svg"/></center></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>3</crumb></trail> <anchor>16097</anchor> <rss>jms-00CQ.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00CQ</addr>  <route>jms-00CQ.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">an algebra</link> for an endofunctor <tex>{ \mathcal{C} } \xrightarrow{{ F }} { \mathcal{C} }</tex>, and let <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ x }} { X }</tex> be an endomorphism in <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>. We define the <em>restriction</em> of <tex>X</tex> by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ x }} { X }</tex> to be the <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">algebra</link> <tex>x \cdot   X</tex> whose carrier is <tex>X</tex> with <tex>{ F X } \xrightarrow{{ \alpha _{ x \cdot X } }} { X }</tex> defined to be the following composite:</p><center><img src="resources/c2d224104b36f5afebbe1b13e5162288-web.svg"/></center></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>4</crumb></trail> <anchor>16098</anchor> <rss>jms-00C5.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C5</addr>  <route>jms-00C5.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebra for a monad</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}   \equiv   { \left ( T, \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>. An <em>algebra</em> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> is defined to be a <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor"><tex>T</tex>-algebra</link> <tex>X</tex> satisfying the following unit and associativity laws:</p><center><img src="resources/ec6759e00f9145acf5448e10c3d94449-web.svg"/></center><center><img src="resources/146c1fca85ae1729922b71100b2a58a7-web.svg"/></center></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>5</crumb></trail> <anchor>16099</anchor> <rss>jms-00C8.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C8</addr>  <route>jms-00C8.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Weak algebra for a monad</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We shall refer to an <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">algebra</link> for the underlying endofunctor of a monad as a <em>weak algebra</em>, following <link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">Joyal and Moerdijk</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>6</crumb></trail> <anchor>16100</anchor> <rss>jms-00CF.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00CF</addr>  <route>jms-00CF.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced monad algebra on a fixed point</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>6</crumb> <crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>16101</anchor> <rss>jms-00CD.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CD</addr>  <route>jms-00CD.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">algebraic set theory</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> that is a fixed point, i.e. the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. We may define the <em>induced <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>-algebra</em> <tex>\bar{X}</tex> to have the same carrier object as <tex>X</tex>  and with the algebra map <tex>{ T X } \xrightarrow{{ \alpha _{ \bar{X} } }} { X }</tex> defined as follows:
  <center><img src="resources/388a9d5ed5c889741a26879c822bf4b9-web.svg"/></center></p></mainmatter> </tree><p>We must show that our <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">construction</link> in fact gives rise to a monad algebra.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>6</crumb> <crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>16102</anchor> <rss>jms-00CE.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CE</addr>  <route>jms-00CE.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Unitality of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar{X}</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">unital</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   <p>We are trying to check that the following morphism is an identity:</p>  <center><img src="resources/18a7283b8af0cbf3d5f6eaee61954eb4-web.svg"/></center>  <ol>    <li>We unfold the definition of the algebra map <tex>\alpha _{ \bar{X} }</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/5d3d8ae1dcc448333abbfeea6a368e1c-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We use the unit law for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/1f4274fb7d056d113fe41671531b536a-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Finally, we use the fact that <tex>\pi _{ X }</tex> is inverse to <tex>\alpha _{ X }</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/151d7c5d7211f4df8d089d8f86aa74dc-web.svg"/></center>    </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>6</crumb> <crumb>3</crumb></trail> <anchor>16103</anchor> <rss>jms-00CG.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CG</addr>  <route>jms-00CG.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Associativity of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ \pi _{ X } }} { T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar{X}</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">associative</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   <p>We are trying to check that the following identity holds:</p>  <center><img src="resources/5500d02fb7c14678afdefb45832c6172-web.svg"/></center>  <ol>    <li>      We will start on the right-hand side. We first unfold the definition of the algebra map.
    
      <center><img src="resources/7f42d3fb77f4ba23ecf04b4a9910e6f7-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We use the fact that <tex>\pi _{ X }</tex> inverts <tex>\alpha _{ X }</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/39b7d1cc9d8c163fbfd95a48a0aa4efd-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We use the associativity of the monad <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/560052e2d6d1901f4871de56ea4da72d-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Folding the definition of the algebra map, we have the desired cell.
      <center><img src="resources/3dc1aa454d333bea262feef63eca05cc-web.svg"/></center>    </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>6</crumb> <crumb>4</crumb></trail> <anchor>16104</anchor> <rss>jms-00CH.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Corollary</taxon> <addr>jms-00CH</addr>  <route>jms-00CH.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> is a monad algebra</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar{X}</tex> is in fact a <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   Because it is <link href="jms-00CE.xml" type="local" title="Unitality of the induced monad algebra">unital</link> and <link href="jms-00CG.xml" type="local" title="Associativity of the induced monad algebra">associative</link>.
</block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" root="false"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>6</crumb> <crumb>5</crumb></trail> <anchor>16105</anchor> <rss>jms-00CK.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CK</addr>  <route>jms-00CK.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}   \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>-algebra equipped with an endomap <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ x }} { X } \in \mathcal{C}</tex>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { x \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar{I} } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar{I}</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>x \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CQ.xml" type="local" title="Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms">restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex> along <tex>x</tex>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   <p>Suppose that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { x \cdot X }</tex> is a homomorphism; we must check that the same map tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar{I} } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { X }</tex>.</p>  <ol>    <li>      First, we unfold the definition of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link>.
      <center><img src="resources/4653352faf7df6b3eb3d1ec1c037c54b-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Next, we use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { x \cdot X }</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/a97a72ff7a8a969f51ef826c7301661b-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We unfold the restricted algebra map.
      <center><img src="resources/e2b9d31bceb4c7e366be41a41dcff7f2-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Then we use the associativity law for the algebra <tex>X</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/f7137cfe25f24c8f3438dd8446107d2b-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { x \cdot X }</tex> again.
      <center><img src="resources/936b20bb4d24fe7a5298bf1d1e3c2e6e-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We recall that <tex>\pi _{ I }</tex> and <tex>\alpha _{ I }</tex> are inverse.
      <center><img src="resources/4f2ff4455a306e20d642c1243e330ca1-web.svg"/></center>    </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16106</anchor> <rss>jms-00C6.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C6</addr>  <route>jms-00C6.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebra for an endofunctor</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>F</tex> be an endofunctor on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>; an <em>algebra</em> for <tex>F</tex> is defined to be an object <tex>X \in \mathcal{C}</tex> equipped with a mapping <tex>{ F X } \xrightarrow{{ \alpha _{ X } }} { X }</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16107</anchor> <rss>jms-00CK.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CK</addr>  <route>jms-00CK.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}   \equiv { \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right )}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>-algebra equipped with an endomap <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow{{ x }} { X } \in \mathcal{C}</tex>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { x \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar{I} } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar{I}</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>x \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CQ.xml" type="local" title="Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms">restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex> along <tex>x</tex>.</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline>   <p>Suppose that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { x \cdot X }</tex> is a homomorphism; we must check that the same map tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar{I} } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { X }</tex>.</p>  <ol>    <li>      First, we unfold the definition of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link>.
      <center><img src="resources/4653352faf7df6b3eb3d1ec1c037c54b-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Next, we use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { x \cdot X }</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/a97a72ff7a8a969f51ef826c7301661b-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We unfold the restricted algebra map.
      <center><img src="resources/e2b9d31bceb4c7e366be41a41dcff7f2-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      Then we use the associativity law for the algebra <tex>X</tex>.
      <center><img src="resources/f7137cfe25f24c8f3438dd8446107d2b-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow{{ j }} { x \cdot X }</tex> again.
      <center><img src="resources/936b20bb4d24fe7a5298bf1d1e3c2e6e-web.svg"/></center>    </li>    <li>      We recall that <tex>\pi _{ I }</tex> and <tex>\alpha _{ I }</tex> are inverse.
      <center><img src="resources/4f2ff4455a306e20d642c1243e330ca1-web.svg"/></center>    </li>  </ol></block>  </mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>16108</anchor> <rss>jms-00CC.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00CC</addr>  <route>jms-00CC.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The successor restriction of a successor algebra</title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" title="Algebraic set theory">algebraic set theory</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal{C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be an <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb{T}</tex>. We define the <em>successor restriction</em> of <tex>X</tex> to be the <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> <tex>s \cdot X  : \equiv   s _{ X } \cdot  X</tex> defined by <link href="jms-00CQ.xml" type="local" title="Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms">restricting</link> <tex>X</tex> along its successor map.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>